rt header|Barnstable}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |Source\n|-\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | <strong>County <br /> pop <br /> (2020)</strong>\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n|\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.massachusetts-demographics.com/counties_by_population |access-date = April 6, 2020 | title = Massachusetts Counties by Population | website= Massachusetts Demographics}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Government response ==\n[[File:ASM show at BCEC.agr.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [[Boston Convention and Exposition Center]] (BCEC), pictured during a 2016 conference. The BCEC will be converted to a [[field hospital]].]]\n\nCiting the rapid increase in cases, Governor Charlie Baker declared a [[state of emergency]] for Massachusetts on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/governor-charlie-baker-declares-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-3-10-2020/31356404 | title = Gov. Baker declares state of emergency as Mass. coronavirus cases more than double | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Locke | first = Kaitlyn | url = https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/10/baker-declares-state-of-emergency-92-total-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts | title = Baker Declares State Of Emergency; 92 Total Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WGBH News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> During a press conference on March 14, 2020, Governor Baker established an emergency command center and promised to expand statewide lab testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/14/metro/baker-sets-up-virus-command-center/|title=State figures on testing raise questions about efforts to contain outbreak |website=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker banned all public gatherings of over 25 people, closed all K\u201312 public schools from March 17 through April 7, and banned on-site service at bars and restaurants for the same period.<ref>{{cite news | title = Gov. Baker bans gatherings of over 25 people, orders school closure, restaurants take-out only | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/gov-charlie-baker-massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-15-2020/31647097 | access-date = March 17, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Governor Baker ordered all schools and childcare services to be closed through May 4, extending the original closure by three weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-extension-of-school-and-non-emergency-child-care-program|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Extension of School and Non-Emergency Child Care Program Closures and Steps to Ensure Housing Stability To Support COVID-19 Response|author= Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|publisher=Mass.gov|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced a stay-at-home advisory to be effective from March 24 until April 7. On March 31 the advisory which was extended to May 4.<ref name=\"Feuer\" /> Starting March 31, hotels, motels and online rentals like [[Airbnb]] were ordered to close to recreational travelers so they could be used to house essential workers and displaced residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-extends-non-essential-business-closures-and-executive-branch|title=Baker-Polito Administration Extends Non-Essential Business Closures and Executive Branch Employee Guidance|publisher=Mass.gov}}</ref> The [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] is being prepared as a 1,000-bed [[field hospital]] for COVID-19 patients, including 500 beds for infected homeless patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/02/1000-beds-planned-for-boston-convention-center-to-treat-coronavirus-patients|title=1,000 Beds Planned For Boston Convention Center To Treat Coronavirus Patients|date=April 2, 2020|first=Ally|last=Jarmanning|publisher=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[DCU Center]] in Worcester was set up as a field hospital for recovering COVID-19 patients, overseen by [[UMass Memorial Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/31/dcu-arena-covid-19-field-hospital|title=Worcester's DCU Center Will Become 250-Bed Field Hospital For Stable COVID-19 Patients|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Governor Baker asked travelers from out of state to avoid Massachusetts or to self-quarantine upon arrival for 14 days. Electronic highway signs were activated, and travelers arriving at [[Logan International Airport]], [[Worcester Regional Airport]], and [[South Station]] were given flyers.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/27/baker-out-of-state-quarantine|title=Baker Asks Visitors To Self-Isolate For Two Weeks \u2014 Or Not Come At All|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref> Medical students were graduated early, and emergency orders were issued giving some nurses with more than two years of experience authority to write prescriptions, and granting incoming medical residents and interns 90-day medical licenses.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\" />\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Registry of Motor Vehicles]] moved to an appointment-only system to avoid overcrowding, and the state extended deadlines for many renewals by 60 days to reduce the need for in-person transactions. With visits down about 90%, eight of the 30 RMV branches closed completely. The National Association of Government Employees, representing customer service employees at the RMV, asked that the remaining offices be closed for worker safety, but the Secretary of Transportation said essential workers needed the RMV to continue operating.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/rmv-workers-union-calls-agency-shutter-all-branches/ RMV workers union calls for agency to shutter all branches]</ref>\n\n== Economic and social effects ==\nThe sudden surge of cases in Massachusetts during the week of March 9 led many organizations to order employees to work from home, and prompted museums and libraries to close. This led to a noticeable decline in Boston's rush hour traffic; in some cases, drive times for major highways dropped by 30 to 50 percent.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/11/boston-traffic-coronavirus | title = Coronavirus: Here's how much Boston's rush hour traffic has dropped &#124; Boston.com | website = Boston.com}}</ref> [[Panic buying]], especially since the week of March 11, led to shortages of some products, and there were crowds and long lines at grocery stores as early in the day as 7:00{{Nbsp}}a.m.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/store-shelves-picked-clean-people-panic-buy-goods-local-supermarkets/ | title = Store shelves picked clean as people panic-buy goods at local supermarkets |newspaper= The Boston Globe | access-date = April 6, 2020 | date= March 13, 2020 | first= Steve |last=Annear |first2=Janelle |last2=Nanos}}</ref> Some grocery retailers such as [[Stop & Shop]] adjusted their hours to allow employees more time to restock and to offer older and more vulnerable people a time where they can shop separately.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-stop-and-shop-senior-hours/ |title=Stop & Shop Creates Hours Only For Customers 60 And Older During Coronavirus Pandemic |date=March 16, 2020 |website=CBS Boston}}</ref> Later, grocery stores implemented stricter measures, including limiting the amount of people allowed inside stores at a time, and marking queues to maintain social distancing. <!--- https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-market-basket-social-distance/ ---> When people in parks were found to not be following social distancing resulted in many parks and playgrounds being closed. Some cities went as far as to remove or block off basketball hoops and other amenities to discourage people from gathering. <!--- https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/29/marty-walsh-boston-parks-coronavirus ---> Beaches and their parking lots were also ordered to close. <!--- https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/02/metro/parking-lots-state-beaches-are-closing/ ---> On April 5, 2020, Boston's mayor, Marty Walsh, issued a stay-at-home advisory for the city of Boston. All non-essential workers were ordered to stay home from 9:00{{Nbsp}}p.m. to 6:00{{Nbsp}}a.m., starting April 6. People were encouraged to wear masks when outside the home, but instructed to leave medical masks for essential workers and make their own if necessary. All baseball, tennis, and hockey fields in parks were ordered to be closed. Residents were instructed not to visit family or fields outside of their households. The restrictions are enforceable by fines.<ref name=\"WGBH-Curfew\" />\n\n{{As of|2020|04|10|df=US|alt=As of April 10}}, eight deaths have been reported at Jack Satter House in [[Revere, Massachusetts|Revere]], a nursing home run by Hebrew Senior Life. Other nursing homes are also reporting confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boston-area senior housing community with Jewish ties reports 6 coronavirus deaths |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/boston-area-senior-housing-community-under-jewish-auspices-reports-6-coronavirus-deaths |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus cases at senior centers and nursing homes in Massachusetts are rising: 'It's a hot zone' - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/01/nation/covid-deaths-senior-centers-nursing-homes-rise/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hebrewseniorlife.org/about-us/covid-19-coronavirus-guidance/jack-satter-house-covid-19-update|title=Jack Satter House - COVID-19 Update|last=|first=|date=|website=Hebrew Senior Life|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== School closures ===\nSchool closures began in early March, when Massachusetts Institute of Technology announced on March 9 that it was moving to only-online classes for the remainder of the spring semester.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\" /> Also on March 9, two elementary schools in the [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]] school district and one in [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] were closed for the day due to COVID-19 tests being conducted on two parents and one child.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cuoco | first = John | url = https://whdh.com/news/multiple-massachusetts-schools-closed-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-rise/ | title = Multiple Massachusetts schools closed Monday as coronavirus cases continue to rise | date = March 9, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> School districts began closing on March 11. Within a week, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/massachusetts-coronavirus-update-schools-closing-or-changing-schedules-for-monday-march-16.html|title=Massachusetts coronavirus update: Schools closing or changing schedules for Monday, March 16|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 13, 2020|website=MassLive|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-and-massachusetts-updated-list-of-massachusetts-colleges-with-canceled-classes-plans-to-switch-to-online-instruction-march-13.html|title=Coronavirus and Massachusetts: Updated list of Massachusetts colleges with canceled classes, plans to switch to online instruction (March 13)|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nWellesley and Framingham closed their public schools and libraries for two weeks on March 13.<ref>{{cite web | title = WPS Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/wps-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Town of Wellesley COVID-19 Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/town-of-wellesley-covid-19-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=2023 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/37162/Press-Release---COVID-19-Update-031320204265 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 13, Boston announced that its public schools would close for six weeks from Tuesday, March 17 through April 26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Public Schools to close Tuesday, with plans to reopen April 27 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/mayor-walsh-address-coronavirus-outbreak-friday-evening/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17 through April 7.<ref name=\"Becker\" /> On March 25, extended the closing through May 4.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baker: schools to open no sooner than May 4th |url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/baker-schools-to-open-no-sooner-than-may/article_dfa2979c-6ed0-11ea-8d2f-9f9402f5677e.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=www.westernmassnews.com |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12, and [[Major League Baseball]] canceled the remainder of spring training. On March 16, after the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] recommended restricting events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, the major league baseball season was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back | title = Opening of regular season to be pushed back | first = Mark | last = Feinsand | website = [[MLB.com]] | date = March 16, 2020 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games | title = Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days | date = March 12, 2020 | website = ESPN.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[National Hockey League]] season was suspended indefinitely.<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> Boston Celtics player [[Marcus Smart]] announced on March 18 that he had tested positive for COVID-19, having been tested five days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/boston-celtics-player-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-team-confirms/31792637|title=Celtics' Marcus Smart tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], which was originally scheduled to take place on April 20, was postponed to September 14. This was the first postponement of the Boston Marathon since it was first held in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28897435/boston-marathon-postponed-sept-14-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title = Boston Marathon postponed until Sept. 14 amid coronavirus concerns|website = ESPN|date = March 13, 2020|accessdate = March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n* [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]]\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Information and Resources | website=[[Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education]] | url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/sfs/emergencyplan/covid19.html }}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:2020 in Massachusetts|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Health in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Qwerty325", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril:copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Massachusetts"}
{"title_page": "Ashok Jhunjhunwala", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox scientist \n| name = Ashok Jhunjhunwala\n| image = \n| caption = Dr. Ashok Jhunjhunwala\n| birth_date = \t{{birth date|df=yes|1953|6|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Kolkata]], [[India]]\n| residence = [[India]]\n| nationality =  [[India]]n\n| field = [[Electrical Engineering]] and [[Telecommunications]]\n| work_institution = Department of Electrical Engineering, [[IIT Madras]], [[TeNet Group|TeNeT Group]]\n| alma_mater = [[IIT Kanpur]], [[University of Maine]]\n| Prizes = [[Padma Shri]] (2002)\n}}\n\n'''Ashok Jhunjhunwala''' is a professor in the Department of Electrical Engineering, [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]] at Chennai, India and has served as the departmental chair.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-09-29/pune/27319085_1_award-valiathan-telecom|title=Jhunjhunwala, Valiathan win H.K. Firodia awards|date=29 September 2002|work=[[Indiatimes]]|accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe leads the Telecommunications and Computer Networks group (TeNeT<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tenet.res.in/|title=The Telecommunications and Computer Networking Group|last=|first=|date=|website=The Telecommunications and Computer Networking Group|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>) at [[IIT Madras]]. This group is closely working with industry in the development of a number of Telecommunications and Computer Network Systems. TeNeT group has incubated a number of technology companies (like DesiCrew Solutions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://desicrew.in/|title=DesiCrew|last=|first=|date=|website=Desi Crew|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>) which work in partnership with TeNeT group to develop Telecom Access products. The group has also incubated a company which aims to install and operate telephone and internet in every village in India.\n\nHe is a director on the board of [[State Bank of India]]. He is also a board member of several Telecom and IT companies in India, including [[Sasken]], [[National Research Development Corporation|NRDC]], and [[IDRBT]]. He is a former board member of [[VSNL]] & [[BSNL]].\n\n== EV Leader ==\nSince 2016, Prof Jhunjhunwala is leading the efforts of bringing EVs in the country. He believes that youth can make an important contribution in maintaining the GDP of Automobile sector of India and must be promoted to come up with innovative ideas. He nurtures several startups and groups to develop new batteries and EV models.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pluginindia.com/blogs/india-is-ready-for-the-ev-revolution-are-you|title=Ashok Jhunjhunwala - India is ready for the EV revolution. Are you?|last=|first=|date=11 Nov 2017|website=PlugInIndia|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He has been proposing to grasp low hanging fruits first exploiting the technical knowledge of our engineers (e.g. designing BMS, battery packaging) and keep shifting to high investments propositions as and when technology is in house available (e.g. of cell manufacturing). He proposed battery swapping model for public transportation \n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/india/iit-madras-testing-prototype-swappable-electric-battery-1502573973.html|title=IIT Madras testing prototype of swappable electric battery|last=|first=|date=27 January 2018|website=The Statesman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nAshok Jhunjhunwala was born in Kolkata on 22 June 1953 in a Marwari family. His grandfather was a Gandhian and a close associate of [[Vinoba Bhave]] and worked with [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lakshmi|first=Krupa|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-metroplus/the-sky-is-his-limit/article4294292.ece|title=The sky is his limit|date=10 January 2013|work=The Hindu|accessdate=3 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe studied in St Lawrence High School in Kolkata (formerly Calcutta) in India, completing the Higher Secondary examination in 1970. He received his B.Tech degree from [[IIT Kanpur]], and his MS and Ph.D degrees from the [[University of Maine]].  From 1979 to 1981, he was with [[Washington State University]] as Assistant Professor. Since 1981, he has been teaching at [[IIT Madras]].\n\n==Contributions in technology innovation==\n\nAshok Jhunjhunwala had contributed in the field of technology and had been on various boards. He advises several technology companies and government agencies in [[India]] <ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=922408&privcapId=22889859|title=Bloomberg News: Profile of Ashok Jhunjhunwala, Ph.D.|date=|work=|accessdate=3 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ee.iitm.ac.in/~ashok/|title=IITM Ashok Jhunjhunwala|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tenet.res.in/Aboutus/People/Faculty/personalPages/ashok.php/|title=Biography Ashok Jhunjhunwala Tenet group|accessdate=3 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315015003/http://www.tenet.res.in/Aboutus/People/Faculty/personalPages/ashok.php|archive-date=15 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nJhunjhunwala was elected as an International Member to the National Academy of Engineering in 2018 <ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nae.edu/178238/Professor-Ashok-Jhunjhunwala|title=For innovation and development of affordable technology solutions in communications and energy.|date=7 February 2018|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe was named JC Bose Fellowship in 2010<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ee.iitm.ac.in/~ashok/|title=Ashok Jhunjhunwala Biography IITM|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was an IEEE Fellow in 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://services27.ieee.org/fellowsdirectory|title=Fellow, IEEE|last=|first=|date=|website=14 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe was Governor of the [http://iccc.org/ International Council for Computer Communication Inc]., (ICCC) from 1999\u20132005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insaindia.org/detail.php?id=P00-1278|title=Indian National Science Academy|accessdate=3 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402174715/http://www.insaindia.org/detail.php?id=P00-1278|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded the Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize in 1998<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=http://ssbprize.gov.in/Content/Detail.aspx?AID=489|title=Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize for Science and Technology|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links and Sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061106080136/http://www.tenet.res.in/Aboutus/People/Faculty/personalPages/ashok.php Tenet Bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120818064656/http://www.ee.iitm.ac.in/facs_ashok IITM Bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070107163100/http://www.acacia.org.za/jhunjhunwala.htm Acacia bio]\n*[http://www.rediff.com/news/2002/mar/27inter.htm News article about Dr. Jhunjhunwala]\n{{SSBPST recipients in Engineering Science}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jhunjhunwala, Ashok}}\n[[Category:Indian academics]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in science & engineering]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Award in Engineering Science]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox scientist \n| name = Ashok Jhunjhunwala\n| image = \n| caption = Dr. Ashok Jhunjhunwala\n| birth_date = \t{{birth date|df=yes|1953|6|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Kolkata]], [[India]]\n| residence = [[India]]\n| nationality =  [[India]]n\n| field = [[Electrical Engineering]] and [[Telecommunications]]\n| work_institution = Department of Electrical Engineering, [[IIT Madras]], [[TeNet Group|TeNeT Group]]\n| alma_mater = [[IIT Kanpur]], [[University of Maine]]\n| Prizes = [[Padma Shri]] (2002)\n}}\n\n'''Ashok Jhunjhunwala''' is a professor in the Department of Electrical Engineering, [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]] at Chennai, India and has served as the departmental chair.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-09-29/pune/27319085_1_award-valiathan-telecom|title=Jhunjhunwala, Valiathan win H.K. Firodia awards|date=29 September 2002|work=[[Indiatimes]]|accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe leads the Telecommunications and Computer Networks group ([http://www.tenet.res.in/ TeNeT]) at [[IIT Madras]]. This group is closely working with industry in the development of a number of Telecommunications and Computer Network Systems. TeNeT group has incubated a number of technology companies (like [https://desicrew.in/ DesiCrew Solutions]) which work in partnership with TeNeT group to develop Telecom Access products. The group has also incubated a company which aims to install and operate telephone and internet in every village in India.\n\nHe is a director on the board of [[State Bank of India]]. He is also a board member of several Telecom and IT companies in India, including [[Sasken]], [[National Research Development Corporation|NRDC]], and [[IDRBT]]. He is a former board member of [[VSNL]] & [[BSNL]].\n\n== EV Leader ==\nSince 2016, Prof Jhunjhunwala is leading the efforts of bringing EVs in the country. He believes that youth can make an important contribution in maintaining the GDP of Automobile sector of India and must be promoted to come up with innovative ideas. He nurtures several startups and groups to develop new batteries and EV models.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pluginindia.com/blogs/india-is-ready-for-the-ev-revolution-are-you|title=Ashok Jhunjhunwala - India is ready for the EV revolution. Are you?|last=|first=|date=11 Nov 2017|website=PlugInIndia|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He has been proposing to grasp low hanging fruits first exploiting the technical knowledge of our engineers (e.g. designing BMS, battery packaging) and keep shifting to high investments propositions as and when technology is in house available (e.g. of cell manufacturing). He proposed battery swapping model for public transportation \n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/india/iit-madras-testing-prototype-swappable-electric-battery-1502573973.html|title=IIT Madras testing prototype of swappable electric battery|last=|first=|date=27 January 2018|website=The Statesman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nAshok Jhunjhunwala was born in Kolkata on 22 June 1953 in a Marwari family. His grandfather was a Gandhian and a close associate of [[Vinoba Bhave]] and worked with [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lakshmi|first=Krupa|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-metroplus/the-sky-is-his-limit/article4294292.ece|title=The sky is his limit|date=10 January 2013|work=The Hindu|accessdate=3 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe studied in St Lawrence High School in Kolkata (formerly Calcutta) in India, completing the Higher Secondary examination in 1970. He received his B.Tech degree from [[IIT Kanpur]], and his MS and Ph.D degrees from the [[University of Maine]].  From 1979 to 1981, he was with [[Washington State University]] as Assistant Professor. Since 1981, he has been teaching at [[IIT Madras]].\n\n==Contributions in technology innovation==\n\nAshok Jhunjhunwala had contributed in the field of technology and had been on various boards. He advises several technology companies and government agencies in [[India]] <ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=922408&privcapId=22889859|title=Bloomberg News: Profile of Ashok Jhunjhunwala, Ph.D.|date=|work=|accessdate=3 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ee.iitm.ac.in/~ashok/|title=IITM Ashok Jhunjhunwala|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tenet.res.in/Aboutus/People/Faculty/personalPages/ashok.php/|title=Biography Ashok Jhunjhunwala Tenet group|accessdate=3 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315015003/http://www.tenet.res.in/Aboutus/People/Faculty/personalPages/ashok.php|archive-date=15 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nJhunjhunwala was elected as an International Member to the National Academy of Engineering in 2018 <ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nae.edu/178238/Professor-Ashok-Jhunjhunwala|title=For innovation and development of affordable technology solutions in communications and energy.|date=7 February 2018|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe was named JC Bose Fellowship in 2010<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ee.iitm.ac.in/~ashok/|title=Ashok Jhunjhunwala Biography IITM|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was an IEEE Fellow in 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://services27.ieee.org/fellowsdirectory|title=Fellow, IEEE|last=|first=|date=|website=14 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe was Governor of the [http://iccc.org/ International Council for Computer Communication Inc]., (ICCC) from 1999\u20132005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insaindia.org/detail.php?id=P00-1278|title=Indian National Science Academy|accessdate=3 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402174715/http://www.insaindia.org/detail.php?id=P00-1278|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded the Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize in 1998<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=http://ssbprize.gov.in/Content/Detail.aspx?AID=489|title=Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize for Science and Technology|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links and Sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061106080136/http://www.tenet.res.in/Aboutus/People/Faculty/personalPages/ashok.php Tenet Bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120818064656/http://www.ee.iitm.ac.in/facs_ashok IITM Bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070107163100/http://www.acacia.org.za/jhunjhunwala.htm Acacia bio]\n*[http://www.rediff.com/news/2002/mar/27inter.htm News article about Dr. Jhunjhunwala]\n{{SSBPST recipients in Engineering Science}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jhunjhunwala, Ashok}}\n[[Category:Indian academics]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in science & engineering]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Award in Engineering Science]]\n", "name_user": "Dg432", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected links to external sites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashok_Jhunjhunwala"}
{"title_page": "Fantasy of Flight", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n |name = Fantasy of Flight\n |image = File:New Standard D-25 1931 9 Waldo Wright Fantasy of Flight Splash ramp SNFSI FOF 15April2010 (14630315535).jpg\n |caption = Aerial view of the site\n |coordinates = {{coord|28.171192|-81.808787|display=inline}}\n |map_type = Florida#USA\n |established = {{start date and age|1995|11|11}}\n |dissolved = \n |location = [[Polk City, Florida]]\n |type = Aviation attraction\n |collection = over 150 aircraft\n |visitors = \n |founder = [[Kermit Weeks]]\n |director = \n |president = \n |curator = \n |publictransit = \n |network =\n |website = {{URL|fantasyofflight.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Fantasy of Flight''' is an [[aviation]]-related attraction in [[Polk City, Florida|Polk City]], [[Florida]], United States that takes visitors back to the pioneering days of early flight, along with the [[World War I|First]] and [[World War II|Second]] world wars and beyond.  The attraction opened in November 1995, and houses the world's largest private aircraft collection on display. It became the new home for much of owner [[Kermit Weeks]]' collection of aircraft that were previously housed at the Weeks Air Museum in [[Kendall-Tamiami Executive Airport|Tamiami]], Florida and were damaged to varying degrees by [[Hurricane Andrew]] in 1992. On April 6, 2014, the attraction was closed to the public, though it is still being maintained and is available for private events. On January 30, 2015, Fantasy of Flight opened a scaled-down museum attraction to display some of their aircraft to the public in the interim while the rest of the facility is upgraded and planned to reopen sometime in the future.<ref name=\"General Aviation News\">{{cite web|url=http://generalaviationnews.com/2014/03/10/general-aviation-in-the-marketplace/|title= General aviation in the marketplace |publisher=General Aviation News/ |date= |accessdate=2013-03-14}}</ref>\n\nFantasy of Flight was the only attraction in the world to offer daily aerial demonstrations (weather permitting) of aircraft in its collection. Most of Weeks' aircraft are airworthy and may still be seen flying from one of the facility's grass runways or its seaplane runway. Fantasy of Flight fields more airworthy aircraft than the air forces of Austria, Cuba, Denmark, Kuwait, Portugal, or South Africa. It also fields more airworthy [[fixed-wing aircraft]] than either the [[Royal Navy]] or the [[Indian Navy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uknda.org/my_documents/my_files/RAF_TheWorldsAirForces1.1.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-04-20 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091117034441/http://www.uknda.org/my_documents/my_files/RAF_TheWorldsAirForces1.1.pdf |archive-date=2009-11-17 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Facility ==\n[[File:Map of Fantasy of Flight.png|thumb|General Layout of Fantasy of Flight]]\nThe facility features a main building consisting of two large hangars (called \"North\" and \"South\") for the aircraft on display; restoration shops; the immersion environments; a gift shop; and the [[Art Deco]] themed Compass Rose Diner. Just outside the main building across from the entrance is the facility's new [[ropes course]] and [[zip line]] attraction known as \"Wing Walk Air.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://totalorlando.com/beyonddetail-3-3-Fantasy_of_Flight.html |title=Fantasy of Flight \u2013 Florida Air Museums \u2013 Orlando \u2013 Kermit Weeks \u2013 Best Vacation Guide |publisher=Totalorlando.com |date= |access-date=2013-02-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020021209/http://www.totalorlando.com/beyonddetail-3-3-Fantasy_of_Flight.html |archive-date=2012-10-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOutside the hangars there is an adjoining tarmac and two grass runways. On the north side of the runways are a maintenance hangar and conference facility. A \"back lot\" to the south of the main complex contains warehouses and storage and restoration facilities. More storage facilities are located across Broadway Blvd and are opened to the public as part of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kermit |url=http://blog.kermitweeks.com/?p=4161 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701163556/http://blog.kermitweeks.com/?p=4161 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-01 |title=New Storage Facility and Tour! &#124; Kermit's Blog |publisher=Blog.kermitweeks.com |date=2012-02-16 |access-date=2013-02-02 }}</ref> Lake Agnes is also on the property to allow for seaplane operations, with a designated landing/takeoff area on 18/36 and a ramp to taxiway on the eastern shore.\n\n== Aircraft operations ==\n[[File:A321, Boeing Stearman PT-17 biplane, Fantasy of Flight, Polk City, Florida, USA, 2010.JPG|thumb|Boeing PT-17 Stearman]]\nThe airfield is officially known as the \"Orlampa Inc. Airport\" and uses the airport identifier \"FA08.\" The field sits at an estimated elevation of 129 feet (42 meters). It is designated as private use only and special permission is needed to land there. The field is generally closed to all non-company traffic. The airfield consists of two turf [[runway]]s: runway 4/22 (5090 x 125&nbsp;ft. / 1551 x 38 m) and runway 14/32 (2500 x 100&nbsp;ft. / 762 x 30 m). The airfield appears as \"Orlampa\" on the [[Jacksonville]] [[sectional chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airnav.com/airport/FA08 |title=FA08 \u2013 Orlampa Inc Airport |publisher=AirNav |date= |accessdate=2013-02-02}}</ref> The name \"Orlampa\" was originated by [[Kermit Weeks]] based on the airfield being approximately midway between the cities of [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]].\n\nWaldo Wright's Flying Service offers airplane rides for sale from the Fantasy of Flight field during parts of the year and operates a [[Boeing-Stearman Model 75|Boeing PT-17 Stearman]] and a [[New Standard D-25]]. The Boeing Stearman is used for 30 minute long 'hands-on experience' flights, in which the customer takes control of the aircraft at some point during the flight. The New Standard D-25 is used for 15 minute [[barnstorming]] flights, in which up to four customers sit in the forward open cockpit of the aircraft as a qualified pilot flies the aircraft.\n\n== Collection ==\nThe Fantasy of Flight collection contains the following aircraft, although the aircraft are not always present at the museum. Some are on loan to other facilities, others may be flown to events, and still others may be off display for maintenance or restoration. Most of the collection is contained in the north and south hangars which are now closed to the public, with a smaller portion now on display at the interim museum attraction housed in the old maintenance hangar. In 2012, the \"Golden Hill\" storage facility attraction opened just across the road from the main facility. A number of aircraft have been re-located into this new building, notably the [[B-23 Dragon]] and the [[B-29 Superfortress]] nose section, while the buildings were re-arranged in order to allow visitor access, but this section was part of the main facility closure in 2014.<ref name=\"Facebook\">{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/fantasyofflight |title=Fantasy of Flight \u2013 Polk City, FL \u2013 Public Places & Attractions, Museum |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2013-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kermit Week's Albatros D.Va.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Kermit Weeks boards his Albatros D.Va in preparation for its first flight at Fantasy of Flight|Kermit Weeks boards his Albatros D.Va in preparation for its first flight at Fantasy of Flight]]\n[[File:Fantasy of Flight Aircraft.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Fantasy of Flight's Bell 47G displayed in foreground, Supermarine Spitfire Mk.16 behind, and Cierva C.30A autogyro in the upper right. The B-26 stands in the background.|Fantasy of Flight's Bell 47G displayed in foreground, Supermarine Spitfire Mk.16 behind, and Cierva C.30A autogyro in the upper right. The B-26 stands in the background.]]\n[[File:Standard J-1 BelowL FOF 14Dec09 (14590672655).jpg|thumb|right|alt=This Standard J-1 appeared in the films The Spirit of St. Louis and The Great Waldo Pepper.|This Standard J-1 appeared in the films ''The Spirit of St. Louis'' and ''The Great Waldo Pepper''.]]\n[[File:Stinson SM-6000B Trimotor NC11170 RSideFront FOF 24Aug09 (14587029191).jpg|thumb|right|alt=One of only two remaining Stinson Tri-Motors.|One of only two remaining Stinson Tri-Motors.]]\n[[File:Martin B-26 Marauder 40-1464 N4297J LSideFront FOF 11Feb2012 (14403956398).jpg|thumb|right|alt=The last remaining airworthy B-26 Marauder.|The last remaining airworthy B-26 Marauder.]]\n[[File:North American P-51C-10-NT Mustang Ina the Macon Belle BelowLFront Outside FOF 19Feb2010 (14403932750).jpg|thumb|right|alt=One of three remaining airworthy P-51C Mustangs in the world.|One of three remaining airworthy P-51C Mustangs in the world.]]\n[[Image:Ffsunderland.jpg|thumb|right|alt=The last remaining airworthy Sunderland.|The last remaining airworthy Sunderland.]]\n[[File:Fantasy of Flight's PBY Catalina.jpg|thumb|right|alt=The PBY Catalina with the main building and North Hangar in the background.|The PBY Catalina with the main building and North Hangar in the background.]]\n[[File:Fantasy of Flight's Lockheed Vega.jpg|thumb|right|alt=The Lockheed Vega painted in the scheme of Wiley Post's Winnie Mae.|The Lockheed Vega painted in the scheme of Wiley Post's Winnie Mae.]]\n\n*[[Hot Air Balloon|Aerostar Balloon]] \u2013 ''N69FF''\n*[[Airco DH.4]] \u2013 On display as U.S. Mail plane.\n*[[Albatros D.V]]a \u2013 ''reproduction''  (original [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] 6cyl, 200&nbsp;hp engine) built by [[Peter Jackson]]\u2019s aviation shop, The Vintage Aviator Ltd.\n*[[Antonov An-2]] \u2013 ''N4301U''\n*[[Avro Cadet]] \u2013 ''N643AV'' \u2013 This is one of eleven remaining Australian Cadets and one of only four which are still flying.<ref>[[Avro Cadet#Survivors|Surviving Avro Cadets]]</ref>\n*[[Avro Lancaster]] \u2013 ''KB976'' \u2013 Stored in a number of shipping boxes behind the museum's workshop. Nose was guillotined from the main body after a hangar collapse at [[Woodford Aerodrome]] in 1987. KB976 made the last official [[RCAF]] flight of this type with [[Flight Lieutenant]] [[Lynn Garrison]] as captain and Flt Lt Ralph Langemann as co-pilot during an air show in Calgary, Alberta July 4, 1964.\n*[[Bachem Ba 349 Natter]] \u2013 ''reproduction''\n*[[ASL Valkyrie|\"Barber\" Valkyrie]] \u2013 ''reproduction''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantasyofflight.com/aircraftpages/valkyrie.htm|title=1911 Barber Valkyrie replica |first=|last=Clark/Nikdel/Powell|website=Fantasy of Flight|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Beechcraft Model 17 Staggerwing]] \u2013 ''N52962'' \u2013 On display at the [[Florida Air Museum]] at [[Lakeland Linder International Airport]].\n*[[Beechcraft Model 18|Beechcraft AT-11 Kansan]] \u2013 ''N92KC''\n*[[Bell P-39 Airacobra]] \u2013 Under off site restoration.\n*[[Bell 47G]] [[Helicopter]] \u2013 ''N147DP'' \u2013 On display in [[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H 4077]] paint scheme.\n*[[Bell P-63 Kingcobra]] \u2013 ''N91448'' \u2013 Formerly on loan to the [[Florida Air Museum]], the plane was partially disassembled and returned to Fantasy of Flight on March 13, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=628918390510577&set=a.628918333843916.1073742120.271937182875368&type=1&theater|title= Kermit Weeks' Facebook Page |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref>\n*[[Benoist XIV]] \u2013 Full size reproduction was built at Fantasy of Flight in an attempt to recreate the [[St. Petersburg-Tampa Airboat Line|first scheduled airline service]] (using a winged aircraft) on the 100th anniversary of its first flight on January 1, 2014. Though the plane was completely assembled and taxi tested, the plane could not achieve the necessary speed to lift off and was not flown at the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.591539734248443.1073742096.271937182875368&type=3|title= Kermit Weeks' Facebook Page |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref>\n*[[Boeing 100]] \u2013 Under off site restoration to flight status after being damaged by [[Hurricane Andrew]] at the former '''Weeks Air Museum'''.\n*[[Boeing B-17G Flying Fortress]] \u2013 On display as USAAF Ser. No. 42-37994 (tail # 237994), \"Piccadilly Princess.\" The B-17 \"Susie Q\" is in storage.\n*[[Boeing B-29 Superfortress]] / [[Boeing B-29 Superfortress variants|Boeing P2B-1S]] ([[U.S. Navy]] variant of the B-29) \u2013 USAAF Ser. No. 45-21787 and USN/USMC [[Bureau Number]] (BuNo) 84029 [[List of surviving Boeing B-29 Superfortresses#Notable individual aircraft|\"Fertile Myrtle\"]]. Aircraft transferred from [[USAAF]] to [[USN]].  Restored cockpit and forward fuselage section on display along with other disassembled fuselage sections in storage at Fantasy of Flight's \"Golden Hill\" facility pending aircraft's restoration to airworthy at a date to be determined.\n*[[Brown B-2 Racer]] \u2013 ''reproduction'' \u2013 Original aircraft destroyed in crash in 1939.\n*[[B\u00fccker B\u00fc 181|Bucker Bestmann]] \u2013 ''N181BU'' \u2013 One of two remaining flying originals.\n*[[B\u00fccker B\u00fc 131|Bucker Jungmann]] \u2013 ''N41455''\n*[[B\u00fccker B\u00fc 133|Bucker Jungmeister]] \u2013 ''N40BJ'' \u2013 On display in the colors of Romanian aerobatic pilot, [[Alexandru Papan\u0103]].\n*[[Vought F4U Corsair|Vought F4U-4 Corsair]] \u2013 On display as BuNo 97286, G5, \"Angel Of Okinawa.\"\n*[[CAC Boomerang]] - Under restoration in Australia\n*[[CAC Wirraway]]\n*[[Cierva C.30A]] [[Autogyro|Autogiro]]\n*[[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Consolidated B-24J Liberator]] \u2013 ''N94459'' \"Joe\" can be seen on the tram tour in the Maintenance Hangar. A B-24 nose is on display in the Officer's Club event facility adjacent to the North Hangar.\n*[[Consolidated PBY Catalina|Consolidated PBY-5A Catalina]] \u2013 ''N96UC'' is on display on the tarmac. An additional PBY is in storage.\n*[[Curtiss JN-4|Curtiss JN-4D Jenny]] \u2013 ''N2404''\n*[[Curtiss Model D|Curtiss Headless Pusher]] \u2013 ''reproduction''\n*[[Curtiss P-40 Warhawk|Curtiss TP-40N Warhawk]] \u2013 ''N923'' \u2013 The only factory-built dual-control TP-40 flying in the world today.\n*[[Curtiss Robin]] \u2013 ''NC8313''\n*[[Curtiss Junior|Curtiss Wright Junior]] \u2013 ''N10967''\n*[[Curtiss-Wright CW-19]] ''N19RX'' \u2013 Delivered to Fantasy of Flight in March 2013. Made its first flight in 2014 and still undergoing testing.\n*[[Curtiss-Wright CW-22]] ''N888U'' was on display at one time in the main hangar but is currently in the Golden Hill Facility<ref>{{cite web|author=Kermit |url=http://blog.kermitweeks.com/?p=2447 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120716024816/http://blog.kermitweeks.com/?p=2447 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-16 |title=Tico Airshow in the TP-40N! &#124; Kermit's Blog |publisher=Blog.kermitweeks.com |date=2012-01-23 |access-date=2013-02-02 }}</ref>\n*[[de Havilland Mosquito]] - Mk B. 35 - RS''712 -'' Displayed ''o''n long-term loan at [[EAA AirVenture Museum]] in [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]].\n*[[de Havilland Vampire]] \u2013 In storage.\n*[[Douglas B-23 Dragon]] \u2013 One of eight remaining in the world. In storage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasyofflight.com/aircraftpages/b23dragon.htm|title=Douglas B-23 Dragon|first=|last=Clark/Nikdel/Powell|website=Fantasy of Flight|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Douglas C-47 Skytrain]] \u2013 ''N1944A'' \n*Douglas DC-3 - On display, advertising Fantasy of Flight, standing alongside Interstate 4.\n*[[Douglas SBD Dauntless|Douglas A-24B Banshee]] \u2013 [[USAAF]] version of the [[USN]]/[[United States Marine Corps|USMC]] [[Douglas SBD Dauntless]], USAAF Ser. No. \"42-54643\" \u2013 In storage\n*[[EKW C-36]] \u2013 In storage\n*[[Fairey Swordfish|Fairey Swordfish IV]] \u2013 In storage\n*[[Fieseler Fi 156|Fieseler Fi-156 Storch]] \u2013 ''N156FS''\n*[[Fieseler Fi-103|Fieseler Fi-103 V-1 Flying Bomb]] \u201